column1: Exocytosis of glutamate receptors around post-synaptic membrane
column7: We observed exocytosis of glutamate receptors around the post-synaptic membrane with total internal reflection fluorescence microscopy. Cultured fat neurons were transfected with GluA1-SEP, glutamate receptor tagged by pH sensitive green fluorescent protein, super ecliptic pHluorin (SEP), and Homer 1C-RFP (a post-synaptic marker). SEP shows fluorescence signals under neutral pH conditions such as an extracellular solution; these signals disappear under acidic conditions such as the internal lumen of vesicles. It was therefore used as an exocytosis marker. Arrows and arrowheads indicate exocytosis around and out of the post-synaptic membrane. Images were acquired every second, and are played at 33 times normal speed. Scale bar is 5 µm.

column1: Endocytosis of glutamate receptors around post-synaptic membrane
column7: We observed endocytosis of glutamate receptors around the post-synaptic membrane using total internal reflection fluorescence microscopy. Cultured rat neurons were transfected with GluA-SEP, glutamate receptor tagged by pH-sensitive green fluorescent protein, super ecliptic pHluorin (SEP), and PSD95-TagRFPt (a post-synaptic marker). SEP shows fluorescence signals under neutral pH conditions such as extracellular solutions and the lumen of newly formed endocytic vesicles; these signals disappear under acidic conditions. In this video, cell-surface GluA-SEP signals were removed to visualize newly formed vesicles by changing the extracellular pH (7.4) to an acidic pH (6.0) every 4 sec. Images at pH 7.4 and pH 6.0 were acquired alternatively every 2 sec. Chemical stimulation inducing endocytosis was applied at 0 sec. Arrows and arrowheads indicate endocytosis around and out of the post-synaptic membrane, respectively. Scale bar is 5 µm, and the video is played at 132 times normal speed.

column7: The nucleosome is a protein-DNA complex that enables cells to compact DNA so that the nucleus can include the whole genome. This video is based on the result of a computational simulation of nucleosome sliding. With a uniform sequence, DNA slides in a corkscrew-like manner according to its helical path. To see how it moves, some nucleotides are colored in red.

The nucleosome is a protein-DNA complex that enables cells to compact DNA so that the nucleus can include the whole genome. This video is based on the result of a computational simulation of nucleosome sliding. With a strong positioning sequence, the DNA slides without following a corkscrew-like motion. Because DNA with a positioning sequence favors a bent shape along the nucleosome, it jumps without rotation. In the video, the positioning motifs that favor an inward-facing configuration are colored in red.

column1: Power stroke motion of a cytoplasmic dynein
column7: The cytoplasmic dynein is a molecular motor that walks on a microtubule by consuming energy from ATPs and changing its conformation. Because structural changes in dynein cannot be observed in biochemical experiments, we used molecular dynamics simulations to reveal the mechanisms of these structural changes. This video shows the results of our computational simulations. In this video, each domain is represented by a specific color and the brightness of the color indicates its state.

column1: Modeling bacterial DNA replication initiation complex by molecular dynamics simulation
column7: Chromosomal replication is a dynamic process that is initiated by DNA unwinding. To understand the DNA unwinding mechanism at replication initiation, we studied the formation of the structure of a DNA-protein complex at the replication origin. This is called the replication initiation complex. In the video, we modeled a part of the initiation complex by coarse-grained molecular dynamics simulation. In the video, DNA is shown in gray and DNA-bending protein (Integration Host Factor) is shown in black. The molecules that form a pentamer on the DNA are DnaA proteins. For visibility, we colored DnaA proteins in two alternating ways: blue (oligomerization domain) and light purple (DNA-binding domain); or green (oligomerization domain) and yellowish green (DNA-binding domain).

column1: Social behavior of flying lizards in Borneo (1)
column7: Male flying lizards have a colored dewlap under their throat. They communicate with each other using several stereotyped dewlap extension patterns. These patterns are species specific, and the dewlap can extend to advertise their territory, perform male-male combat, and court females. Males also exhibit a stereotyped push-up display, which is a ritualized display used for advertisement of their territory and male-male combat.

column1: Wing morphology and color of flying lizards
column7: Each wing of a flying lizard is supported by about six ribs, and can be spread and closed like a fan. The dorsal and ventral sides of the wings have a species-specific color, and the color of the ventral side is often different between males and females. This video shows a juvenile male.

column1: Defensive displays in Japanese tiger snakes in relation to nuchal glands
column7: The Japanese tiger snake has unique defensive organs, called nuchal glands, under the skin of the neck region. Nuchal glands contain toxic steroids. This snake shows unique defensive displays such as neck flattening, neck arching, and dorsal facing posture, which would enhance the predation evasion effects of the nuchal gland toxins.

column1: Fighting behavior of a snake for food resource (1)
column7: Akamata snakes living on remote islands of Okinawa exploit sea turtle hatchlings on a beach. They detect nests of sea turtles and excavate sea turtle hatchlings that are going to emerge to the sand’s surface.

column1: Fighting behavior of a snake for food resource (2)
column7: Akamata snakes also eat sea turtle eggs accidentally exposed to the sand’s surface. On such occasions, snakes and hermit crabs, which are very common on the beach, compete with each other to rob the eggs to eat.

column1: Predatory behavior of a snake on sea turtle hatchings (1)
column7: Snakes are mainly solitary animals, and individual interactions are very rare except for the reproductive period, when males combat each other to gain mates. However, Akamata snakes living on remote islands of Okinawa exhibit fighting behaviors to gain access to food resources. While they eat hatchling sea turtles in the nest and on the beach, they perform a ritualized combat dance if two individuals come across each other.

column1: Predatory behavior of a snake on sea turtle hatchings (2)

column1: Predation avoidance by tail autotomy in lizards
column7: Many lizard species voluntarily break their tail. This behavior is called autotomy, and is used as an antipredator tactic. Such a lizard often autotomizes its tail when the tail is bitten by a predator such as a snake. While the snake is swallowing the autotomized tail, the lizard is able to escape and seek refuge.

Decapitation of termites by Brahminy blindsnake
column7: Almost all species of snakes swallow their prey whole, but there are a few exceptions. The brahminy blind snake (Indotyphlops braminus) adroitly decapitates its termite prey and consumes the thorax and abdomen while discarding the head, which is hard to digest and may contain toxic compounds.

The tiger keelback (Rhabdophis tigrinus) possesses unusual structures known as nuchal glands in the skin of the dorsal neck. Nuchal glands may contain potent cardiac steroids (bufadienolides) that are secreted when this species is attacked by a predator. The unique anti-predator behaviors of R. tigrinus, such as exposing the neck and neck butting, are presumably associated with the chemical defense of the nuchal glands. Caution: R. tigrinus is not only poisonous but also venomous. It is opisthoglyphous (rear-fanged), and its bite can be fatal to humans.

column1: Gestation-related changes in foraging and diet in tiger keelback
column7: The tiger keelback (Rhabdophis tigrinus) sequesters anti-predator defensive compounds from toads (Bufo), which are consumed as prey in addition to other amphibian prey. Females of R. tigrinus are able to produce chemically defended offspring by provisioning the toad-derived toxins to their eggs. Females of R. tigrinus switch foraging behaviors according to the seasons and selectively forage for toads during gestation.

column7: The mother–infant bond is strong. Infants are carried by their mothers until they are 4 or 5 years old.

column1: A female extending her hand to a male for greeting
column7: A female extending her hand to a male as a greeting. Chimpanzees show various greeting behaviors.
There are cultural differences in social behaviors (e.g., grooming). This image shows a style of grooming (grooming hand clasp) in the Mahale Mountains National Park.
A kind of chimpanzee tool use (ant fishing). Tool use patterns differ from place to place.
Chimpanzees gathering at the red colobus monkey they have hunted. The main food for chimpanzees is ripe fruits, but they also love meats.

column1: Polyspecific association between Japanese macaques and sika deer in Yakushima Island
column7: In Yakushima Island, sika deer approach Japanese macaques to eat plant seeds and macaque feces. This polyspecific association occurs during the day and at night.

column1: Foraging behavior of Japanese macaques on unripe fruits of Myrica rubra in Yakushima Island
column7: Japanese macaques forage fruits of various plant species and they disperse seeds through spitting or defecation. However, macaques also break the seeds of unripe fruit.

column1: Social grooming cluster including four individuals of Japanese macaques in Yakushima Island
column7: Among Japanese macaques, social grooming usually occurs between two individuals, and they occasionally show polyadic (3+ monkeys) grooming.

column1: Ash falls by the eruption of Mt. Shindake in Kuchinoerabu Island and Japanese macaques on Yakushima Island
column7: Mt. Shindake on Kuchinoerabu Island erupted on May 29, 2015. The volcanic ash reached Yakushima Island, which is inhabited by Japanese macaques, and rained down on the forest floor and plant leaves.

column1: Long-sightedness in old Japanese macaques during grooming
column7: Japanese macaques pick and eat lice (Pedicinus obtusus and Pedicinus eurygaster) and lice eggs. Aged macaques seem to have presbyopia because the distance between their eyes and hands becomes longer.

column1: An all-male grouop of Japanese macaques living in Kinkazan Island, Japan
column7: Male Japanese macaques live as non-troop males during some periods of their life while repeatedly transferring between bisexual groups (i.e., troops). Non-troop males sometimes form all-male groups with other non-troop males. All-male groups are easily found on Kinkazan Island, Japan.

column1: An adult femle Japanese macaques feeding seaweed in Kinkazan Island, Japan
column7: Japanese macaques mainly eat fruits, flowers, and leaves, and these food materials become scarce in the summer and winter. Monkeys on Kinkazan Island, Japan, frequently go down to the seashore and eat seaweed to compensate for the lack of these main food resources during the summer and winter.

column1: An adult female Japanese macaques feeding barkin Mt. Hakusan during winter
column7: Japanese macaques inhabit the most northern latitudinal area among non-human primates, and even live in areas with heavy snow. In snowy seasons, the ground is covered with heavy snow, and they mainly feed on bark and buds.

column1: Mother and infant of Japanese macaques moving in snowy area
column7: Japanese macaques inhabit the most northern latitudinal area among non-human primates, and even live in areas with heavy snow. When the grounds are covered with heavy snow and it becomes difficult to walk, they travel along trails made by other monkeys.

column1: Large resting cluster of Japanese macaques in Shodoshima Island, Japan
column7: Japanese macaques form a huddling cluster, called “Saru-dango,” with others while they are resting. Monkeys in Shodoshima, Japan, are known to form extra-large huddling clusters.

column1: Bathing into hot spring by Japanese macaques in Jigokudani, Japan
column7: In Jigokudani, Japan, we can see Japanese macaques enter hot springs to warm their bodies during a cold winter.

column1: Onset and exchange of grooming behavior in Japanese macaques
column7: Grooming among Japanese macaques is sometimes accompanied by solicitation. Grooming is a social interaction with reciprocation because the direction of grooming may change.
Pseudo-feeding behavior can be observed among juvenile Japanese macaques, as with human infants and juveniles.

column1: Stone hundling by an adult female Japanese macaques
column7: Japanese macaques sometimes strike or rub stones held by both hands. This behavior is called stone handling and is considered to be a kind of displacement behavior.

column1: An adult male of Hainan rhesus macaques
column7: Rhesus macaques (Macaca mulatta brevicaudatus) on Hainan Island, China, have the smallest body size among six sub-species of rhesus macaques. They are closely related to Japanese macaques, but morphological differences such as tail length can be found.

column1: Mounting behavior among male juvenile Hainan rhesus macaques
column7: Mounting behavior among males has been considered to function as confirmation of dominance hierarchy. However, it might be more appropriate to regard it as a behavior for tension reduction because subordinate males also mount dominant males.

column1: A group of François' langur on the cliff of limestone
column7: François' langurs live in a steep topography made of limestone, and mainly feed on mature leaves. They form single-male and multi-female groups, and use caves on a cliff as sleeping sites.

column1: Progression of a Large Group of Mandrills
column7: Wild mandrills form very large groups of 300 to 800 individuals, which are among the largest primate groups.

column1: Mandrills in the Moukalaba-Doudou National Park, Gabon
column7: Mandrill groups consist mostly of females and immature individuals. Most males live by themselves. During the mating seasons, males form groups and mate with females with sexual swellings.

column1: Chloroplast-targeted Holliday junction resolvases govern the faithful inheritance of chloroplast nucleoids.
column7: Holliday junctions, four-stranded DNA structures formed during homologous recombination, are disentangled by resolvases that have been found in prokaryotes and eukaryotes but not in plant organelles. Here, we identify monokaryotic chloroplast 1 (MOC1) as a Holliday junction resolvase in chloroplasts by analyzing a green alga (Chlamydomonas reinhardtii) mutant defective in chloroplast nucleoid (DNA-protein complex) segregation (A). MOC1 is structurally similar to a bacterial Holliday junction resolvase, resistance to ultraviolet (Ruv) C, and genetically conserved among green plants. Reduced or no expression of MOC1 in Arabidopsis thaliana leads to growth defects and aberrant chloroplast nucleoid segregation. In vitro biochemical analysis and high-speed atomic force microscopic analysis revealed that A. thaliana MOC 1 (AtMOC1) binds and cleaves the core of Holliday junctions symmetrically (B). MOC1 may mediate chloroplast nucleoid segregation in green plants by resolving Holliday junctions.

column1: A medaka embryo expressing GFP gene driven by promoter of ER stress sensor IRE1a
column7: ER stress sensor IRE1a activates the unfolded protein response to keep homeostasis in the endoplasmic reticulum. IRE1a is ubiquitously expressed. By this reason, EGFP fluorescent driven by IRE1a promoter is observed ubiquitously.
